  "title": "Sociology of the Holocaust",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fd7dd1c2ce128363",
      "text": "[…] Modern genocide pursues a higher goal. The elimination of the enemy is a means to an end, a necessity that arises from the overriding objective: This goal is the vision of a better, fundamentally transformed society. Modern genocide is an element of \"social engineering\" aimed at realizing a social order that corresponds to the design of a perfect society. The planners and leaders of modern genocide see society as an object of purposeful precalculation that requires more than isolated design interventions and repairs. The goal is more ambitious and more radical: the aim is to recreate society in order to force it into an overarching scheme based on scientific knowledge. A new society is to be created that is \"objectively\" superior to its \"vegetating\" counterpart. Of course, this social design has an aesthetic dimension – the forthcoming ideal world can only be measured by the [[Standard of Beauty]] itself. A new world that resembles a perfect work of art that (...) cannot be improved either by adding, by omitting or by changing\" (Bauman, op. cit., p.106). Action in this meaning is oriented towards abstractions, towards ideals that do not exist in reality, towards ideas that have found their highest expression in the figures of thought of Western science."
